Dave Mielke, le mer. 19 févr. 2020 18:10:35 -0500, a ecrit:
 [quoted lines by Mario Lang on 2020/02/19 at 13:00 -0800]
 >You can view, comment on, or merge this pull request online at:
 >
 >  #247
 >
 >-- Commit Summary --
 >
 >  * API connection settings fields should be const char. (ml)

 I myself agree with you but, the last time this issue came up, Samuel and
 Sébastien didn't.
Oh, I didn't remember.
 I believe the argument was that assigning a malloc()ed string needs to
 be supported.
Looking back in my mails, I find this:

«
it means for instance that if somebody wants to do something like:

brlapi_connectionSettings_t *parameters(some args) {
        brlapi_connectionSettings_t *ret = malloc(sizeof(*ret));
        asprintf(&ret->auth, "%something", args...);
        return ret;
}

freeparameters(settings) {
        free(settings->auth);
        free(settings);
}

int main(void) {
        brlapi_connectionSettings_t * settings = fillparameters(args...);
        brlapi_openConnection(settings);
        freeparameters(settings);
}

He'd now have to put casts in various places to avoid warnings, making
programming more tedious than needed.  In general, one can see that libc
etc. never put consts in structures etc. even if it would make sense,
because of that problem.

Since these consts will not be very useful for optimization anyway
(while they will in other places you have changed), I think they would
bring more harm than good here.
»

Mario, does putting const here actually avoid some casts in your code,
or is it mostly about documenting the ownership?

Samuel

